  "text": "To say that two concepts have similar semantics ... means roughly that they occupy similar places in their lattices. A problem with the above is, however, clear: ontology alignment is defined in terms of correspondence (equivalence, sameness, similarity) of concepts. But how, precisely, do we gain access to concepts in order to determine whether they stand in a relation correspondence? (p. 146) [CITATION_1] found that the majority of studies are based on the vocabulary (i.e., the words-with the above-mentioned problems) or on the structure of the KOS (e.g., similar broader terms and similar narrower terms). Counting common words and common concepts is a good idea on a theoretical level, but when it comes to practical application, a problem arises.",
